3. Apply TDIDF weighting on the term document matrix. Next, apply latent semantic analysis on the term document matrix. Generate MDS plots corresponding to these matrices

tf-idf weighting and MDS Plot:

td.mat = as.matrix(td.mat)
td.mat.w = lw_tf(td.mat) * gw_idf(td.mat)  ## tf-idf weighting
dist.mat = dist(t(as.matrix(td.mat.w))) ## compute distance matrix

# generate mds plot using new distance matrix
doc.mds <- cmdscale(dist.mat, k = 2)
data <- data.frame(x = doc.mds[, 1], y = doc.mds[, 2], topic = df$Topic, id = row.names(df))
ggplot(data, aes(x = x, y = y, color=topic)) + geom_point()

LSA and MDS Plot:

lsa.space = lsa(td.mat.w, dims=3)  ## create LSA space
dist.mat = dist(t(as.textmatrix(lsa.space)))  ## compute distance matrix

doc.mds = cmdscale(dist.mat, k = 2)
data = data.frame(x = doc.mds[, 1], y = doc.mds[, 2], topic = df$Topic, id = row.names(df))
ggplot(data, aes(x = x, y = y, color=topic)) + geom_point()

4. Write down your observation based on these two plots.

Answer:

For the first MDS plot before doing the weighting, it shows that the four topics are slightly clustered together with some outliers.
After weighting, both MDS plots of tf-idf weighting and LSA indicate strong relationships between each topics due to the similarity of the association among words.

Task 2 (Recommendation): create a recommender system based on the book rating data available here: http://www2.informatik.uni-freiburg.de/~cziegler/BX/. In the dataset, load the BX-Book-Ratings.csv and BX-Books.csv data. Extract books published from 1998 to present. Create a book rating matrix from these books, and in this matrix, only consider books that were rated by at least 10 users, and users that rated at least 10 books.

1. Run and test a recommender system built with different recommendation methods, including random, popular, user-based collaborative filtering, item-based collaborative filtering. Evaluate the different methods by using k-fold cross-validation (k = 4). Generate a performance table in terms of performance measures MAE, MSE, and RMSE. Hint: use “recommenderlab” library. Documentation can be found here: https://www.rdocumentation.org/packages/recommenderlab/versions/0.2-4

First of all, I did some data processing and cleaning by using some java codes (because it will lead to various problems when we read the original data set into Rstudio).

To process the “BX-Books.csv”:

import java.io.*;

public class BooksHandle {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        File file = new File("D:/workspace/r/INFSCI 2160 Data Mining/Week05/BX-Books - Copy.csv");
        BufferedReader reader;
        String outputName = "D:/workspace/r/INFSCI 2160 Data Mining/Week05/BX-Books - New.csv";
        BufferedWriter writer;
        try {
            File output = new File(outputName);
            if (!output.exists()) {
                File dir = new File(output.getParent());
                dir.mkdirs();
                output.createNewFile();
            }
            reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file));
            writer = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter(outputName));
            String line;
            while ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) {
                line = line.replace("\"", "'");
                line = line.replace("';'", "\";\"");
                line = line.replaceFirst("'", "\"");
                line = line.substring(0, line.length() - 1) + "\"";
                writer.write(line);
                writer.newLine();
            }
            writer.close();
            reader.close();
        } catch (IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

To process the “BX-Book-Ratings.csv”:

import java.io.*;

public class RatingsHandle {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        File file = new File("D:/workspace/r/INFSCI 2160 Data Mining/Week05/BX-Book-Ratings - Copy.csv");
        BufferedReader reader;
        String outputName = "D:/workspace/r/INFSCI 2160 Data Mining/Week05/BX-Book-Ratings - New.csv";
        BufferedWriter writer;
        try {
            File output = new File(outputName);
            if (!output.exists()) {
                File dir = new File(output.getParent());
                dir.mkdirs();
                output.createNewFile();
            }
            reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(file));
            writer = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter(outputName));
            String line;
            while ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) {
                line = line.replace("\"", "'");
                line = line.replace("';'", "\";\"");
                line = line.replaceFirst("'", "\"");
                line = line.substring(0, line.length() - 1) + "\"";
                line = line.replace("'", "");
                line = line.replace("\" ", "\"");
                line = line.replace("\"\\", "\"");
                line = line.replace("\\\"", "\"");
                line = line.replace("#", "");
                line = line.replace("(", "");
                line = line.replace(")", "");
                line = line.replace("+", "");
                line = line.replace("`", "");
                line = line.replace("=", "");
                line = line.replace("-", "");
                line = line.replace(" ", "");
                line = line.replace(".", "");
                line = line.replace("*", "");
                line = line.replace(",", "");
                line = line.replace("/", "");
                line = line.replace("_", "");
                line = line.replace(":", "");
                line = line.replace("@", "");
                writer.write(line);
                writer.newLine();
            }
            writer.close();
            reader.close();
        } catch (IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

Extract books published from 1998 to present.

ratings <- read.csv('BX-Book-Ratings - New.csv', header = T, sep = ';', stringsAsFactors = T)
books <- read.csv('BX-Books - New.csv', header = T, sep = ';', stringsAsFactors = T)

df <- books[books$Year.Of.Publication >= 1998, ]
summary(df$Year.Of.Publication)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    1998    1999    2001    2001    2002    2050
ratings.df <- ratings[ratings$ISBN %in% df$ISBN,]

Due to the data discription, “Ratings (‘Book-Rating’) are either explicit, expressed on a scale from 1-10 (higher values denoting higher appreciation), or implicit, expressed by 0.”, I filter the ratings which is 0 because they are implicit.

ratings.df <- ratings.df[ratings.df$BookRating > 0,]

Only consider books that were rated by at least 10 users, and users that rated at least 10 books. I use a while-loop to implement this.

len <- 0
while (len != nrow(ratings.df)) {
    len <- nrow(ratings.df)
    ratings.books <- data.frame(table(ratings.df$ISBN))
    ratings.books <- ratings.books[ratings.books$Freq > 0,]
    ratings.users <- data.frame(table(ratings.df$UserID))
    colnames(ratings.books) <- c('ISBN', 'Freq')
    val_books <- ratings.books[ratings.books$Freq >= 10, 'ISBN']
    ratings.df <- ratings.df[ratings.df$ISBN %in% val_books,]
    colnames(ratings.users) <- c('UserID', 'Freq')
    val_users <- ratings.users[ratings.users$Freq >= 10, 'UserID']
    ratings.df <- ratings.df[ratings.df$UserID %in% val_users,]
}

Then run and evaluate a recommender system built with different recommendation methods, including random, popular, user-based collaborative filtering, item-based collaborative filtering.

r <- as(ratings.df, "realRatingMatrix")
r
## 731 x 697 rating matrix of class 'realRatingMatrix' with 13264 ratings.
hist(getRatings(r), breaks=10)

hist(getRatings(normalize(r)), breaks=100)

hist(getRatings(normalize(r, method="Z-score")), breaks=100)

hist(rowCounts(r), breaks=100)

## comparison of several recommender algorithms
set.seed(12)
scheme <- evaluationScheme(r, method="cross-validation", k=4, given=-1, goodRating=10)
scheme
## Evaluation scheme using all-but-1 items
## Method: 'cross-validation' with 4 run(s).
## Good ratings: >=10.000000
## Data set: 731 x 697 rating matrix of class 'realRatingMatrix' with 13264 ratings.
algorithms <- list(
    "random items" = list(name="RANDOM", param=NULL),
    "popular items" = list(name="POPULAR", param=NULL),
    "user-based CF" = list(name="UBCF", param=list(nn=50)),
    "item-based CF" = list(name="IBCF", param=list(k=50))
)


## run algorithms
results <- evaluate(scheme, algorithms, type = "topNList", n=c(1:20))

2. Write down your observations based on the final performance table.

Answer:

Popular and UBCF are more efficient than Random and IBCF for this dataset.
For the top 5 items, UBCF have a better performance than Popular, but the performance will reduce after the 6th item.
The TPR of IBCF does not increase until the 12th item, and in the precision/recall plot, the precision drops vertically before the 12th item.
